  "prompt": "What oozes out of a bug bite?",
  "response": "When a bug bite occurs, the body reacts to the insect's saliva or venom, which can cause inflammation and irritation. If the bite becomes infected or if the immune response leads to the formation of a blister, you might see a clear fluid oozing from the bite. This fluid can be lymph or pus, which is composed of dead white blood cells, bacteria, and tissue debris. It's important to keep the area clean to prevent infection. If there's significant discharge, increased redness, swelling, or discomfort, consulting a healthcare professional is advisable.",
